[{"id":30357,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Haloalkanes and Haloarenes","question":"","options":["$\\mathrm{Br}^{-}>\\mathrm{I}^{-}>\\mathrm{Cl}^{-}$","$\\mathrm{I}^{-}>\\mathrm{Br}^{-}>\\mathrm{Cl}^{-}$","$\\mathrm{Cl}^{-}>\\mathrm{Br}^{-}>\\mathrm{I}^{-}$","$\\mathrm{Cl}^{-}>\\mathrm{I}^{-}>\\mathrm{Br}^{-}$"],"answer":1,"solution":"Since the leaving group breaks away as a base, it is easier to displace weaker bases as compared to stronger bases. Thus less basic the substituent, the more easily it is displaced.\nSince the basic strength of the given groups is in order.\n$\\mathrm{I}^{-} < \\mathrm{Br}^{-} < \\mathrm{Cl}^{-}$\nThus the order of halogen leaving groups is\n$\\mathrm{I}^{-}>\\mathrm{Br}^{-}>\\mathrm{Cl}^{-}$","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2013 (25 Apr Online)","image":null},{"id":30364,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Haloalkanes and Haloarenes","question":"","options":["<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/BY5zsGTm3tH4Jb3Qgc4OT3sOGj-_hEpWohjUWog2fSc.original.fullsize.png\"><br>","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/ZccRYc7WNsZ2Qm4p17jrre55rJ4ui8FtsS0D-ZbUSbs.original.fullsize.png\"><br>","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/xsc1BIad7OFcwogw6C9UwlORbBE8Rek-VQZGfjVWobY.original.fullsize.png\"><br>","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/nAyn3Gc9FxfoAEgKKyiOIMBZQMBiTi3YN7AbYP-g9Kc.original.fullsize.png\"><br>"],"answer":3,"solution":"$$\n\\mathrm{Ag}>\\mathrm{Hg}>\\mathrm{Cu}\n$$\n<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/XSLGf25q1dpNUZnVQJhXEYJtZqgsUszarNl9OOoHFgE.original.fullsize.png\"><br>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2012 (19 May Online)","image":null},{"id":30375,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Haloalkanes and Haloarenes","question":"","options":["$\\mathrm{CH}_3 \\mathrm{CHO}$ and $\\mathrm{CH}_3 \\mathrm{Br}$","$\\mathrm{BrCH}_2 \\mathrm{CHO}$ and $\\mathrm{CH}_3 \\mathrm{OH}$","$\\mathrm{BrCH}_2-\\mathrm{CH}_2-\\mathrm{OCH}_3$","$\\mathrm{H}_3 \\mathrm{C}-\\mathrm{CHBr}-\\mathrm{OCH}_3$"],"answer":3,"solution":"<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/C5nK6MRAWDg4b1cLOnTJXBzFRtMZ8DrRu-9wiDu2C1M.original.fullsize.png\"><br>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2006","image":null},{"id":30293,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Haloalkanes and Haloarenes","question":"","options":["<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/11eec806-568a-427e-ad74-11fa415dc9f5-image.png\" style=\"width: 317px; height: 174px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/9b0f6483-399e-47c4-b598-0066516993d9-image.png\" style=\"width: 403px; height: 174px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/a0806077-3e70-4abb-8fc4-e4938dc912e6-image.png\" style=\"width: 403px; height: 174px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/a2e7fa48-95c4-4212-8e17-49d5c2c1460a-image.png\" style=\"width: 363px; height: 174px;\" />"],"answer":3,"solution":"<p>When the reaction is carried out in solvents of low polarity such as <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>CHCl</mi><mn>3</mn></msub></math> or <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>CS</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></math> and at low temperature, monobromophenols are formed.&nbsp;</p><p>When phenol is treated with bromine water,<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#160;</mo><mn>2</mn><mo>,</mo><mn>4</mn><mo>,</mo><mn>6</mn><mo>-</mo></math> tribromophenol is formed as white precipitate.&nbsp;</p><p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/d65e82cc-c2a7-4ecf-8543-a9a44ef12eb0-image.png\" style=\"width: 392px; height: 335px;\" /></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2021 (26 Aug Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":30301,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Haloalkanes and Haloarenes","question":"","options":["<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/52e715c1-4f0e-461c-806b-988e66cb7365-image.png\" style=\"width: 250px; height: 90px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/844907ed-d875-4406-b17a-10c7d423fcac-image.png\" style=\"width: 318px; height: 60px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/05595fee-6466-47ec-aafc-49f063ab6cab-image.png\" style=\"width: 269px; height: 60px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/310647a8-daa0-4a96-8cc8-634443699c37-image.png\" style=\"width: 169px; height: 59px;\" />"],"answer":0,"solution":"<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/79c31642-9b1f-41e3-936a-690299e3c3f9-image.png\" style=\"width: 422px; height: 75px;\" />","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2021 (24 Feb Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":30281,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Haloalkanes and Haloarenes","question":"","options":["<p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/c055f8c6-cc40-4c0e-83b1-82c48a4980f3-image.png\" style=\"width: 120px; height: 169px;\" /></p>","<p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/3b299a74-14d6-4269-88f7-fd890e5b6255-image.png\" style=\"width: 90px; height: 136px;\" /></p>","<p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/86abd234-f6c6-4c6d-83a9-a55ccd3aeeb9-image.png\" style=\"width: 90px; height: 173px;\" /></p>","<p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/79d8dc36-879a-4022-bc00-e1a90195b914-jeeq.png\" style=\"width: 180px; height: 74px;\" /></p>"],"answer":2,"solution":"<p>4-bromotoluene undergoes free radical chlorination,to form 4-bromo benzyl chloride.</p><p>4-bromo benzyl chloride on reaction with KCN from</p><p>&nbsp;4-Bromobenzyl Cyanide which undergoes hydrolysis to form&nbsp;4-Bromophenyl acetic acid,</p><p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/f72586c6-acd8-47fd-b19c-3994695dfb5a-a2acecf4-8f6d-4f55-8506-4f2010a2d96c-image.png\" style=\"width: 440px; height: 119px;\" /></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2022 (28 Jun Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":30229,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Haloalkanes and Haloarenes","question":"","options":["<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/2cNSHIgKUiJmV1HEEubjjQ_l5Gqtpm2YONz0Ky4hgUw.original.fullsize.png\"/><br/>","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/uzH5VcDKZtdKq-fqDBGKih07MKH5LLuNkit47H9aAEg.original.fullsize.png\"/><br/>","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/2dAVRL4mVWivGCBb4_sS91JbSrabffnlfxo5jbPSCLU.original.fullsize.png\"/><br/>","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/7OunbAjtMxkOEk2Vf4ywA2wPkDLWrBahd3Vcooq21iE.original.fullsize.png\"/><br/>"],"answer":2,"solution":"<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/qsVIroMG7BoCeiijuISk_WdRL3zmlQ07nKE6bzdSby8.original.fullsize.png\"><br>\n\n\n\nFormation of more stable free radical intermediate","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2025 (22 Jan Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":30278,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Haloalkanes and Haloarenes","question":"","options":["Both&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi></mfenced></math> and <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">R</mi></mfenced></math>&nbsp;are true and&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">R</mi></mfenced></math>&nbsp;is the correct explanation of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi></mfenced></math>.","Both <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi></mfenced></math>&nbsp;and <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">R</mi></mfenced></math>&nbsp;are true but <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">R</mi></mfenced></math>&nbsp;is not the correct explanation of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi></mfenced></math>.","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi></mfenced></math>&nbsp;is true, but&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">R</mi></mfenced></math> is false.","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi></mfenced></math>&nbsp;is false, but <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">R</mi></mfenced></math>&nbsp;is true."],"answer":2,"solution":"<blockquote><p>Under the Friedel Craft Reaction condition, the aniline (a Lewis base) binds to the electrophile<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#160;</mo><msub><mi>AlCl</mi><mn>3</mn></msub></math> (a Lewis acid) to give a coordination complex (a salt). Then, the positive charge on the nitrogen is electron withdrawing, and it pulls the electron density of the aromatic ring by&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>-</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">I</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mtext>effect</mtext></math>. It therefore, deactivates the ring for further alkylation&nbsp;reactions. Finally, the complex precipitates out of the reaction mixture and the alkylation&nbsp;reaction is not observed.</p><p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/d59d9a23-0911-4ef7-9689-741be11a55d3-image.png\" style=\"width: 342px; height: 180px;\" /></p></blockquote>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2022 (26 Jul Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":30384,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Haloalkanes and Haloarenes","question":"","options":["alkenes","alkyl copper halides","alkanes","alkenyl halides"],"answer":2,"solution":"$\\mathrm{R}_2 \\mathrm{CuLi}+\\mathrm{R}^{\\prime} \\mathrm{X} \\longrightarrow \\mathrm{R}-\\mathrm{R}^{\\prime}+\\mathrm{R}-\\mathrm{Cu}+\\mathrm{LiX}$","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2005","image":null},{"id":30258,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Haloalkanes and Haloarenes","question":"","options":["<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi></mfenced><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi></mfenced></math>&nbsp;and&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">D</mi></mfenced></math>&nbsp;only</p><p>&nbsp;</p>","<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi></mfenced><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi></mfenced><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi></mfenced></math>&nbsp;and&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">D</mi></mfenced></math></p><p>&nbsp;</p>","<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi></mfenced><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi></mfenced></math>&nbsp;and&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">D</mi></mfenced></math>&nbsp;only</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p>","<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi></mfenced><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi></mfenced></math>&nbsp;and&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">D</mi></mfenced></math>only</p><p>&nbsp;</p>"],"answer":1,"solution":"<blockquote><p>The rate of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">S</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">N</mi></msub><mn>2</mn></math>&nbsp;reaction decreases with increase in steric crowding.&nbsp;In the given set of molecules the second molecule(Tertiary alkyl halide)&nbsp;is sterically crowded, hence, it is correct option. More stable carbocation formed, higher will be the reactivity of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">S</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">N</mi></msub><mn>1</mn></math>. Benzyl carbocation is more reactive than aliphatic carbocation.</p><p>The deactivating groups decreases the rate of electrophilic substitution reaction.&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>NO</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></math> is strong deactivating group for electrophilic substitution.</p><p>In the aromatic nucleophilic substitution reactions, the intermediate formed is carbanion and, it is stabilised by&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>NO</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></math>&nbsp;at ortho or para positions.</p><p>Hence <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">D</mi></math> all are correct.</p></blockquote>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2023 (10 Apr Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":30211,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Haloalkanes and Haloarenes","question":"","options":["","","",""],"answer":3,"solution":"","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2026 (22 January Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":30238,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Haloalkanes and Haloarenes","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/XOI9rGc0HRqvbwBElSnmqFJ4pQGBr5VPq5o2Ql9EO3s.original.fullsize.png\"><br><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/UlzhvulM5TuiG_k05AhEsejFA9sqb0l5APx3732NWkU.original.fullsize.png\"><br>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2024 (06 Apr Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":30248,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Haloalkanes and Haloarenes","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"<blockquote><p>Optical activity is the ability of a substance to rotate the plane of polarisation of a beam of light that is passed through it.A compound to be said as optically active is only if it has to have an asymmetric chiral carbon centre (the carbon is said to be chiral if they have different substituents attached).</p><p>The optically active substances that rotate the plane of polarisation of the light towards the right are known as right-handed or dextrorotatory. It can be Indicated by including (+) or ‘D’ before the compound name.</p><p>Substances that rotate the plane of polarisation of the light toward the left are known as left-handed or laevorotatory. It can be Indicated by including (-) or ‘L’ before the compound name</p><p>The reaction is as follows,</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>2</mn><mo>-</mo><mi>chlorobutane</mi><mo>+</mo><msub><mi>Cl</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>→</mo><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mn>4</mn></msub><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>8</mn></msub><msub><mi>Cl</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></math> </p><p> <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mn>4</mn></msub><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>8</mn></msub><msub><mi>Cl</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></math> will give four isomers of which one is optically inactive. Their structures are as follows,</p><p> </p><p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/0df55944-2c39-4e2b-a823-35df9ce41de8.png\" style=\"width: 500px; height: 336px;\"/>Here only two, i.e., II and IV are optically active. Since each optically active compound has two enantiomers, therefore, total <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>6</mn></math> isomeric compounds are possible.</p></blockquote>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2024 (30 Jan Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":30329,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Haloalkanes and Haloarenes","question":"","options":["<p><img height=\"96\" src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/6103a50e-3f63-4c16-bcf1-4c1c7b0c8b42-image.png\" width=\"126\" /></p>","<p><img height=\"93\" src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/87c0ca88-8beb-496d-9da5-5313049e547c-image.png\" width=\"92\" /></p>","<p><img height=\"95\" src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/712b9387-63bf-4c91-89a3-c1307a1d92ce-image.png\" width=\"127\" /></p>","<p><img height=\"92\" src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/5196e127-97b8-4937-9920-5794f87b91c1-image.png\" width=\"92\" /></p>"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p><img height=\"197\" src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/ae3c5408-786b-4310-8378-ab7881bb2b4b-image.png\" width=\"628\" /></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2019 (09 Jan Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":30340,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Haloalkanes and Haloarenes","question":"","options":["<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/5923297e-1d76-442b-9e06-44f7c6d8df48-image.png\" style=\"width: 150px; height: 114px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/cba3bb67-9c1e-488c-b1e2-37cfa448bdff-image.png\" style=\"width: 170px; height: 82px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/d69ae38d-8ed2-4c72-9ed7-babd4ae5922d-image.png\" style=\"width: 150px; height: 93px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/800860e7-f308-4737-ad24-9b21dd57e027-image.png\" style=\"width: 130px; height: 84px;\" />"],"answer":3,"solution":"<p>In the options,&nbsp;they have acidic <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#946;</mi><mo>&#8722;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi></math> so&nbsp;an elimination reaction takes place and&nbsp;alkene will be formed.</p><p>And the formed alkene decolourizes&nbsp;the bromine water {<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mover><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">E</mi><mo>&#8853;</mo></mover></math> addition reaction of an alkene by <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>HOBr</mi></math>} while in <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfenced><mn>4</mn></mfenced></math> it does not have <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#946;</mi><mo>&#8722;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi></math>&nbsp;so, there is no formation of alkene, hence does not decolourize&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>Br</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></math>&nbsp;water.</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2017 (02 Apr)","image":null},{"id":30209,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Haloalkanes and Haloarenes","question":"","options":["A-III, B-IV, C-I, D-II","A-I, B-II, C-IV, D-III","A-IV, B-I, C-III, D-II","A-III, B-IV, C-II, D-I"],"answer":3,"solution":"Vinyl Chloride has Cl directly attached to a C=C double bond, matching III: CH₂=CHCl. <br>Benzyl Chloride has CH₂Cl attached to a benzene ring, matching IV (benzene with CH₂Cl substituent). <br>Alkyl Chloride is a general chlorine-substituted alkane, matching II: CH₂-CH(Cl)CH₃ (a standard secondary alkyl chloride). <br>Allyl Chloride has CH₂Cl attached to the allylic position (adjacent to C=C), matching I: CH₂=CH-CH₂Cl. <br>The correct matching is A-III, B-IV, C-II, D-I.","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2026 (24 January Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":30352,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Haloalkanes and Haloarenes","question":"","options":["CH<sub>2</sub> = CH - Br + C<sub>6</sub>H<sub>5</sub> - CH<sub>2</sub>&nbsp;- ONa","C<sub>6</sub>H<sub>5</sub>&nbsp;-&nbsp;CH&nbsp;=&nbsp;CH&nbsp;- Br +&nbsp;CH<sub>3</sub>&nbsp;-&nbsp;ONa","CH<sub>2</sub><sub>&nbsp;</sub>=​&nbsp;CH&nbsp;-&nbsp;CH<sub>2</sub>&nbsp;- Br +&nbsp;C<sub>6</sub>H<sub>5</sub>ONa","C<sub>6</sub>H<sub>5</sub>Br +&nbsp;CH<sub>2</sub>&nbsp;=&nbsp;CH&nbsp;- CH<sub>2</sub>&nbsp;-&nbsp;ONa"],"answer":2,"solution":"<p>It is a Williamson&#39;s ether synthesis reaction. It is a&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">S</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">N</mi></msub><mn>2</mn></math>&nbsp;reaction. Aryl halides will not undergo nucleophilic substitution reactions readily. Hence, allyl-phenyl ether can be prepared by reaction of allyl halide and phenoxide ion as follows</p><p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/9d81acde-820c-4941-bd2e-fdfcbcf50301-image.png\" style=\"width: 392px; height: 86px;\" /></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2014 (09 Apr Online)","image":null},{"id":30360,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Haloalkanes and Haloarenes","question":"","options":["<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/4dmjrEJ9NmlxRJnRfGvbYOvQi3ta7sjwStPT2WCpB8A.original.fullsize.png\"><br>","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/i8cwGF9sBGhZYF-nhx5PQmBwTe6XaLN6xlsDIBFrf6I.original.fullsize.png\"><br>","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/yGr1TzejoHsAJIj5HfJgNVB84Bt9ceEl5Og7x678fnA.original.fullsize.png\"><br>","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/FtY55OxKZ2bwlxLAClltZWDkfk5c5XRgJYH4rJNeySQ.original.fullsize.png\"><br>"],"answer":2,"solution":"<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/00p8gI9_7uQnMAVtn6s8wgWR7J0D_pmkScH87VIoae4.original.fullsize.png\"><br>\n(Since tertiary carbocation is more stable)","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2013 (09 Apr Online)","image":null},{"id":30330,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Haloalkanes and Haloarenes","question":"","options":["<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/36742f5d-49d6-4416-8d0e-1fc16b3626f1-image.png\" style=\"width: 150px; height: 101px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/9aaa4ba4-285f-45e4-b28c-5ed9add445e6-50ba25fc-cac9-4b0d-b137-3347dcece315-image.png\" style=\"width: 187px; height: 119px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/7989e5a7-1476-46db-8c19-5ad5d56b5dbf-image.png\" style=\"width: 130px; height: 102px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/13149fae-21a8-475b-9deb-8644a9405d69-image.png\" style=\"width: 150px; height: 130px;\" />"],"answer":1,"solution":"<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">This is hydrohalogenation reaction of alkene. This is an electrophilic addition reaction. Addition occurs via Markovnikov&#39;s rule.&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>HBr</mi></math> adds to the double bond of the styrene forming 1-bromo-1-phenylethane.</p><p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/e60f2a4f-88b1-4998-99c5-434034b90414-image.png\" style=\"width: 450px; height: 117px;\" /></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2018 (16 Apr Online)","image":null},{"id":30259,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Haloalkanes and Haloarenes","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#62;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi><mo>&#62;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">D</mi><mo>&#62;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mo>&#62;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi><mo>&#62;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">D</mi><mo>&#62;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">D</mi><mo>&#62;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mo>&#62;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi><mo>&#62;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">D</mi><mo>&#62;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi><mo>&#62;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi><mo>&#62;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi></math>"],"answer":3,"solution":"<blockquote><p>The intermediate formed in aromatic nucleophilic substitution reaction is carbanion. Carbanion stabilised by electron withdrawing groups. Aryl halides are less reactive towards nucleophilic aromatic substitution with aqueous <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>NaOH</mi></math>. Introduction of electron releasing group like <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>OCH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub></math>&nbsp;group further decreases its reactivity towards nucleophilic substitution. But the introduction of electron withdrawing groups like <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>NO</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></math>&nbsp;group particularly at the ortho and para position increases its reactivity towards nucleophilic substitution. Higher the number of electron withdrawing groups, higher the reactivity.<br /><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8756;</mo></math> The correct reactivity order is</p><p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/0f9de85c-d9da-40cc-afb6-0bb94851eda8.png\" style=\"width: 500px; height: 107px;\" /></p></blockquote>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2023 (08 Apr Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":30355,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Haloalkanes and Haloarenes","question":"","options":["It is a covalent molecule.","It contains <math> <mrow> <msup> <mtext>Cs</mtext> <mo>+</mo> </msup> </mrow> </math> and <math> <mrow> <msubsup> <mtext>I</mtext> <mn>3</mn> <mo>-</mo> </msubsup> </mrow> </math> ions.","It contains <math> <mrow> <msup> <mtext>Cs</mtext> <mrow> <mn>3</mn> <mo>+</mo> </mrow> </msup> </mrow> </math> and <math> <mrow> <msup> <mtext>I</mtext> <mrow> <mo>-</mo> </mrow> </msup> </mrow> </math> ions.","It contains <math> <mrow> <msup> <mtext>Cs</mtext> <mo>+</mo> </msup> <msup> <mo>, I</mo> <mo>-</mo> </msup> </mrow> </math> and lattice <math> <mrow> <msub> <mtext>I</mtext> <mn>2</mn> </msub> </mrow> </math> molecule."],"answer":1,"solution":"<math> <mrow> <msubsup> <mtext>I</mtext> <mn>3</mn> <mo>-</mo> </msubsup> </mrow> </math> ion is made by the addition of excess iodine to iodide solution.<br /><br /><math> <mrow> <msub> <mtext>I</mtext> <mn>2</mn> </msub> <mo>+</mo> <msup> <mtext>I</mtext> <mo>-</mo> </msup> <mo>→</mo> <msubsup> <mtext>I</mtext> <mn>3</mn> <mo>-</mo> </msubsup> </mrow> </math><br /><br />Cs will always be in +1 oxidation state.","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2014 (06 Apr)","image":null},{"id":30322,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Haloalkanes and Haloarenes","question":"","options":["<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/a04bc934-be5d-428b-87cd-95bc741860f9-image.png\" style=\"width: 120px; height: 187px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/9fbfceea-f5fc-4796-bec5-0f2cfaa0605c-image.png\" style=\"width: 130px; height: 193px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/ab42a41f-ebee-4d26-a7b8-6f6caf53a290-image.png\" style=\"width: 120px; height: 194px;\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/961dcfaf-6c09-422b-8407-1441da7bc7e3-image.png\" style=\"width: 120px; height: 222px;\" />"],"answer":3,"solution":"<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/d86b052e-87b1-4be0-9618-f3c9f301237b-image.png\" style=\"width: 323px; height: 410px;\" />","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2019 (08 Apr Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":30347,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Haloalkanes and Haloarenes","question":"","options":["Swarts reaction","Free radical fluorination","Sandmeyer's  reaction","Finkelstein reaction"],"answer":0,"solution":"Alkyl fluorides is best accomplished by swarts reaction i.e. heating an alkyl chloride/bromide in the presence of metallic fluoride such as AgF, Hg<sub>2</sub>F<sub>2</sub>, CoF<sub>2</sub>, SbF<sub>3</sub>.<br /><br /><math> <mrow> <msub> <mtext>CH</mtext> <mn>3</mn> </msub> <mtext>Br</mtext> <mo>+</mo> <mtext>AgF</mtext> <mo>→</mo> <msub> <mtext>CH</mtext> <mn>3</mn></msub><mtext>F</mtext> <mo>+</mo> <mtext>AgBr</mtext> </mrow> </math>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2015 (04 Apr)","image":null},{"id":30256,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Haloalkanes and Haloarenes","question":"","options":["<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">S</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">N</mi></msub><mn>2</mn><mo>,</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi><mo>=</mo></math>iso-butyl&nbsp;ethyl&nbsp;ether;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">S</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">N</mi></msub><mn>1</mn><mo>,</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi><mo>=</mo></math>tert-butyl ethyl ether</p>","<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">S</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">N</mi></msub><mn>1</mn><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi><mo>=</mo></math>tert-butyl ethyl ether; <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">S</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">N</mi></msub><mn>1</mn><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>2</mn><mo>-</mo></math>butyl ethyl ether</p>","<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">S</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">N</mi></msub><mn>2</mn><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>2</mn><mo>-</mo></math>butyl ethyl ether; <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">S</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">N</mi></msub><mn>2</mn><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi><mo>=</mo></math>iso-butyl ethyl ether</p>","<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">S</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">N</mi></msub><mn>1</mn><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi><mo>=</mo></math>tert-butyl ethyl ether; <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">S</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">N</mi></msub><mn>2</mn><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi><mo>=</mo></math>iso-butyl ethyl ether</p>"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p>The reaction between methyl propyl bromide and <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>5</mn></msub><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mo>-</mo></msup></math> proceeds via an <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">S</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">N</mi></msub><mn>2</mn></math> (substitution nucleophilic bimolecular) mechanism. In this mechanism, the nucleophile attacks the carbon atom bearing the bromine (the electrophilic carbon) in a single step, leading to the displacement of the bromine atom.</p><p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/56eaaed5-8fc6-4c4a-8fb2-4ff7f7beabee.png\" style=\"width: 500px; height: 126px;\" /></p><p>The reaction between methyl propyl bromide and <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>5</mn></msub><mi>OH</mi></math> can proceed via either an <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">S</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">N</mi></msub><mn>1</mn></math> (substitution nucleophilic unimolecular). Here&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>5</mn></msub><mi>OH</mi></math>&nbsp;is a weak nucleophile. During the reaction 1,2-hydrogen shift will occur and tert-butyl ethyl ether is formed.</p><p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/f1d0ecef-f74f-4ec6-9967-5e44c2d2f3f3.png\" style=\"width: 600px; height: 218px;\" /></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2023 (13 Apr Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":30328,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Haloalkanes and Haloarenes","question":"","options":["<p><img height=\"103\" src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/f50acf26-f7b2-4320-9525-a466c38da08b-image.png\" width=\"154\" /></p>","<p><img height=\"99\" src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/cbd3d403-76d9-4483-a1e0-066352d1c001-image.png\" width=\"116\" /></p>","<p><img height=\"93\" src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/d38776c6-ade5-4ad4-96cb-bb4ee60b6cc9-image.png\" width=\"142\" /></p>","<p><img height=\"95\" src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/66fd3b2a-7b7e-494f-9d51-186a67d1885c-image.png\" width=\"135\" /></p>"],"answer":3,"solution":"<p>The first step is anti addition of <math><msub><mrow><mi>B</mi><mi>r</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msub></math> across the double bond.<br /><br /><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/7a45c302-0d57-4092-b3f1-10134ea6095f-qweaa.png\" style=\"width: 372px; height: 115px;\" /><br /><br />In the second step, <math><mi>E</mi><mi>t</mi><msup><mrow><mi>O</mi></mrow><mrow><mo>-</mo></mrow></msup></math> <math><mo>(</mo><mi>n</mi><msup><mrow><mi>u</mi></mrow><mrow><mo>-</mo></mrow></msup></math> ) gets added by <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">S</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">N</mi></msub><mn>1</mn></math> mechanism. And <math><mi>B</mi><msup><mrow><mi>r</mi></mrow><mrow><mo>-</mo></mrow></msup></math> from the dashed position acts as the leaving group leads to the formation of a stable benzylic carbocation.<br /><br /><img height=\"107\" src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/1cc0e7fd-0196-435c-8de4-0b978ced6064-image.png\" width=\"349\" /></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2019 (09 Jan Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":30325,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Haloalkanes and Haloarenes","question":"","options":["<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/nvThtrPMpAnvKlcpd4DthX32CigTpMeveTikMaGUsEA.original.fullsize.png\"><br>","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/cEHrpLm8bdw95qu_qbigwyDtb9bsqA4c3ooXUXS49Gs.original.fullsize.png\"><br>","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/ZP-eOXnWTJw7pV-y4YAe6bSfLO6-mLmgKtNk6AWCIQc.original.fullsize.png\"><br>","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/35ZwgM3xmVO93Yzu09vXKVIW6XKgpnmn9aT8ya_ofhE.original.fullsize.png\"><br>"],"answer":3,"solution":"<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/A4TKY90xX1pDLdaSO5PT9Wy1mfKexvp35_C_yonVSCM.original.fullsize.png\"><br>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2019 (11 Jan Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":30333,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Haloalkanes and Haloarenes","question":"","options":["<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/afoqaxivexvqnfcndxxjppnjvpydgxtxnjuzjphxwwptyjkdrr.jpeg\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/uahfifgzbqixkaxkomkfqjcdnnhwmicozjiultqgnwlmqfothj.jpeg\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/fnhxdzkoajgaiwkmatshtyqadtmzcbrqyyqhzdmbeqjugyzbyf.jpeg\" />","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/httxgizbikwqobeukbppxkcqsagnncssniehyzedcifahikruc.jpeg\" />"],"answer":2,"solution":"<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/b9b0984d-2f3b-4868-88b1-ead79d41d6af-image.png\" style=\"width: 400px; height: 103px;\" /><br /><br /><img alt=\"\" src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/266694.PNG\" style=\"width: 100px; height: 80px;\" />has&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#946;</mi><mo>&#8722;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi></math>. So, elimination will take place.","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2018 (08 Apr)","image":null},{"id":30362,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Haloalkanes and Haloarenes","question":"","options":["Acetone","Propanol-1","Propene","Propanal"],"answer":0,"solution":"<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/CC7fc8IWbvRXfEH-Ut2kHTF1WPnuLEXsd09KSevvuUQ.original.fullsize.png\"><br>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2012 (26 May Online)","image":null},{"id":30279,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Haloalkanes and Haloarenes","question":"","options":["<p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/fb342175-b046-4dac-aa49-c21c21da35f8-image.png\" style=\"width: 93px; height: 120px;\" /></p>","<p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/12e2523a-66e2-4fc7-8bd0-9bfcddd51368-image.png\" style=\"width: 99px; height: 120px;\" /></p>","<p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/5c75a81a-3134-47ba-988f-def90c99a163-image.png\" style=\"width: 95px; height: 120px;\" /></p>","<p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/308b155f-ed9b-48c8-b1c3-9bcff1358f6f-image.png\" style=\"width: 95px; height: 120px;\" /></p>"],"answer":1,"solution":"<blockquote><p>This reaction is an example of Darzen&#39;s reaction. It follows <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">S</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">N</mi></msub><mn>2</mn></math> mechanism. Hence, inversion product is the major product.</p><p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/aa61fd55-3db1-4520-b0d8-a39027f955ab-image.png\" style=\"width: 542px; height: 120px;\" /></p></blockquote>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2022 (25 Jul Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":30287,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Haloalkanes and Haloarenes","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p><img alt=\"\" src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/8152a493-731a-4a61-aec2-4a57b6fe9daf-VARAHIDEVI.png\" style=\"width: 273px; height: 104px;\" /></p><p>S<sub>N<sup>2</sup>&nbsp;</sub>reaction takes place and the number of pi-electrons in the product is 2.</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2022 (24 Jun Shift 2)","image":null}]